    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans, Off the Edge'' (Op-Ed, July 20):</p>
        <p>Larry Rockefeller, a Republican, recites a litany of Republican positions that he disagrees with on issues like tax cuts, estate taxes, deficit spending, abortion, the environment, health care and gun control.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans, Off the Edge'' (Op-Ed, July 20):</p>
        <p>Larry Rockefeller, a Republican, recites a litany of Republican positions that he disagrees with on issues like tax cuts, estate taxes, deficit spending, abortion, the environment, health care and gun control.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Rockefeller is critical of the G.O.P. approach to these ''front burner'' issues, what core issues are left to tie him happily to the Republicans?</p>
        <p>If he thinks like, sounds like and writes like a Democrat, it might be time for him to become one.</p>
        <p>BILL SCHER  Larchmont, N.Y., July 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
